Name: Chalres Bridge
Description: Charles Bridge is a stone Gothic bridge that connects the Old Town and Lesser Town (Mal  Strana). It was actually called the Stone Bridge (Kamenn most) during its first several centuries.

Name: Rialto Bridge

Name: Petronas Twin Towers
Description: The Petronas Towers, also known as the Petronas Twin Towers are twin skyscrapers in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.

Name: Coloseum
Description: Colosseum was commissioned around A.D. 70-72 by Emperor Vespasian of the Flavian dynasty as a gift to the Roman people. In A.D. 80, Vespasians son Titus opened the Colosseum officially known as the Flavian Amphitheater with 100 days of games,

Name: Willis Tower
Description: Willis Tower is the premier corporate office building in Chicago, home to more than 100 companies including prominent law, insurance, transportation and financial services.

Name: Museu Nacional d'Art
Description: The Museu Nacional d'Art de Catalunya is located in the Palau Nacional of Montjuc, constructed for the International Exposition of 1929. In 1934 it opened its doors as the Museu d'Art de Catalunya

Name: St. Peter's Basilica
Description: St. Peters Basilica is one of the holiest temples for Christendom and one of the largest churches in the world. Besides, it is where the Pope presides many liturgies all year round.

Name: Alhambra Palace
Description: The Alhambra is an ancient palace, fortress and citadel located in Granada, Spain. The eighth-century-old site was named for the reddish walls and towers that surrounded the citadel: al-qal'a al-hamra in Arabic means red fort or castle
